subSection.paragraph:
Eriophyoid mites (
Acari
) are a diverse group of plant parasites that are highly adapted for phytophagy. They have an extremely reduced morphology with few remaining setae and only two pairs of legs, and only three active life stages. A large proportion of species induce plant deformities such as erinea, galls or leaf rolling and most are specific to a single species or genus of host plants (Lindquist & Oldfield 
1996
). The host-plant adaptations of eriophyoid mites probably favoured their radiation onto all major groups of vascular plants. Overall, their current classification is largely based on artificially defined groups, in part because their simplified morphology offers limited sets of diagnostic characters (Lindquist & Amrine 
1996
).

The family Phytoptidae (sensu
Amrine et al. 2003
) is a relatively small family of Eriophyoidea and includes taxa that are reputed to be the earliest derivatives of the group. Despite the comparative morphological work of the late Dr Valery G. Shevchenko and his colleagues on phytoptid taxa (
Shevtchenko et al. 1991
;
Sukhareva 1994
;
Bagnjuk et al. 1995
, 1998 ;
Sukhareva & Chetverikov 2010
;
Chetverikov 2012 a
, b ; Chetverikov et al. 2012 ), much remains to be done for understanding the early evolution of the Eriophyoidea . Except for a few Phyllocoptinae and Eriophyinae ( Eriophyidae ) species found in fossil galls in Europe and Australia from the Tertiary period (
Sawada et al. 2007
) and presumably phytoptid mites Triasacarus fedelei
Lindquist and Grimaldi 2012
and Ampezzoa triassica
Lindquist and Grimaldi 2012
found in Triassic amber (Late Carnian: ca. 230 Ma) in the Dolomite Alps of northeastern Italy (
Schmidt et al. 2012
), palaeontological data on eriophyoids are largely lacking. Nevertheless, because eriophyoid ancestors are presumed to have originated on gymnosperms and have diverged into separate lineages following the divergence of angiosperms from gymnosperms, a diverse phytoptid-like fauna may have already been flourishing on vascular plants by the end of the Mesozoic era (
Boczek & Schevchenko 1996
;
Bagnjuk et al. 1998
; Chetverikov et al. 2009 ;
Schmidt et al . 2012
).

subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis . Eriophyoid mites with 1–5 setae on the prodorsal shield, including unpaired or paired vi and/or paired ve setae; usually tibia I solenidion (φ) and opisthosomal subdorsal seta (
c 1
); female genital coverflap usually without ridges; spermathecal tubes short to very elongate (
Amrine et al. 2003
).

