subSection.paragraph:
Eriophyoid mites are among the smallest arthropods in the world, along with members of other acarine groups such as dolichocybids, acarophenacids (Heterostigmata) and tydeids (one of the putative closest relatives to eriophyoids), as well as insect groups such as feather-winged beetles ( Ptiliidae ) and chalcidoid wasps ( Trichogrammatidae and Mymaridae ) (Grebennikov 2008 ;
Polilov & Beutel 2010
;
Walter et al. 2009
). The miniature size of eriophyoids, combined with the presence of complexes of morphologically similar species and the deficiency of reliable diagnostic characters represents a major impediment for alpha-taxonomy and systematic research on eriophyoid mites. The search for new characters and methods of analysis for improving the systematics of Eriophyoidea is one of the major goals of modern eriophyoidology. This can only be achieved through detailed comparative morphological studies across different species and higher taxa.

The morphology of the internal genitalia of eriophyoid mites varies widely among taxa. Hence, their detailed study using modern tools such as CLSM (
Chetverikov 2012 b
) may provide new, meaningful species-level as well as generic and suprageneric characters that are urgently needed for elucidating species boundaries and phylogenetic relationships within the Eriophyoidea . Recently, confocal microscopy has been successfully used for solving taxonomic issues in various invertebrate groups, especially small, more-or-less translucent organisms (or easily rendered as such), some of which are in the size range of eriophyoid mites (e.g. gastrotrichs, Leasi & Todaro 2009 ; nematodes, Fadeeva & Zograf 2010 ), but also for imaging outer and internal structures of larger or more sclerotized arthropods, including those in other mite groups (e.g.
Klaus & Schawaroch 2006
;
Valdecasas 2008
). Other internal features of mites have also been studied using confocal microscopy including the musculature and nervous system (van
Wijk et al. 2006
), and some of them could be taxonomically informative (e.g. pharyngeal muscle pumps in pygmephorids,
Camerik 2001
). However, a distinct specimen-preparation method would typically be required to fix and stain those more poorly sclerotized structures prior to examination. Of great benefit is that through the provision of traditional optical microscopy techniques which utilise specimens mounted in media that tend to clear soft tissues (such as those containing chloral hydrate, for example, Hoyers medium), a relatively straightforward method for observing such internal structures in parallel with external morphology already exists, whereby the more sclerotized elements of the female (and male) reproductive organs can be examined afterwards using CLSM .

For a group that is as diverse, economically important and character-poor as the Eriophyoidea , molecular methods as well as CLSM and 3 D modelling techniques have been surprisingly little used for species delineations and even less so for improving systematics per se (
Navajas & Navia 2010
;
Chetverikov 2012 b
). The COI sequence data produced for
Oziella sibirica
sp. nov.
(available in GenBank under accession number NCBI
JQ 342669
) may help to distinguish related species in the future and perhaps also clarify relationships with close genera (e.g.
Navajas et al. 1996
). However, more slowly evolving markers should also be studied, across phytoptid taxa, since molecular data overall is very badly needed as a supporting tool for eriophyoid systematics. Since many phytoptid taxa inhabit exotic plants that sometimes only have a narrow distribution in remote regions of the world, a revision of the Phytoptidae would have to be conducted through international collaboration. This is even more vital because most modern techniques and associated facilities are not yet widely accessible. Resolving the phylogeny of phytoptid taxa and their relatives ( Phytoptidae is probably not monophyletic) and in turn establishing a classification that reflects natural groupings will help to open the door to evolutionary hypotheses about host plant associations and other life history traits as biological knowledge advances in parallel.

